{"id":"1110.4239","submitter":"Leonardo Giusti","authors":"Leonardo Giusti","title":"Thermal momentum distribution from shifted boundary conditions","comments":"7 pages, 1 figure, contribution to the proceedings of the XXIX\n  International Symposium on Lattice Field Theory - Lattice 2011","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"hep-lat hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  At finite temperature the distribution of the total momentum is an observable\ncharacterizing the thermal state of a field theory, and its cumulants are\nrelated to thermodynamic potentials. In a relativistic system at zero chemical\npotential, for instance, the thermal variance of the total momentum is a direct\nmeasure of the entropy. We relate the generating function of the cumulants to\nthe ratio of a path integral with properly shifted boundary conditions in the\ncompact direction over the ordinary partition function. In this form it is well\nsuited for Monte-Carlo evaluation, and the cumulants can be extracted\nstraightforwardly. We test the method in the SU(3) Yang--Mills theory, and\nobtain the entropy density at three different temperatures.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 19 Oct 2011 10:56:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-10-20"}
